## 1. Introduction

This manual describes how to set up, configure, and use the
{{ product_name | default("OmniSight UVC Camera Module") }} as a USB Video Class
gadget device on an embedded Linux platform.

## 2. Prerequisites

- Linux kernel {{ kernel_version | default("5.10+") }} with ConfigFS and USB gadget support
- Kernel modules: `libcomposite`, `usb_f_uvc`
- USB OTG or device-mode capable SoC
- Python {{ python_version | default("3.10+") }} (for management API)

## 3. Quick Start

### 3.1 Load Kernel Modules

```bash
modprobe libcomposite
modprobe usb_f_uvc
```

### 3.2 Create Gadget via API

```python
from backend.uvc_gadget import UVCGadgetManager, GadgetConfig

config = GadgetConfig(
    gadget_name="{{ gadget_name | default("g_uvc") }}",
    vendor_id=0x{{ vendor_id | default("1d6b") }},
    product_id=0x{{ product_id | default("0104") }},
    manufacturer="{{ manufacturer | default("OmniSight") }}",
    product="{{ product_name | default("UVC Camera") }}",
    serial="{{ serial | default("000000000001") }}",
    max_resolution=(1920, 1080),
    max_fps=30,
)

manager = UVCGadgetManager(config)
manager.create_gadget()
manager.bind_udc()
```

### 3.3 Start Streaming

```python
manager.start_stream(format="h264", width=1920, height=1080, fps=30)
```

### 3.4 Verify on Host

```bash
# Linux host
v4l2-ctl --list-devices
v4l2-ctl -d /dev/video0 --list-formats-ext
ffplay /dev/video0
```

## 4. Configuration Reference

### 4.1 Gadget Configuration

| Parameter | Default | Description |
|-----------|---------|-------------|
| `gadget_name` | `g_uvc` | ConfigFS gadget directory name |
| `vendor_id` | `0x1d6b` | USB Vendor ID |
| `product_id` | `0x0104` | USB Product ID |
| `udc` | auto-detect | USB Device Controller name |
| `max_power` | `500` | Max power in mA |

### 4.2 Video Formats

| Format ID | Name | Description |
|-----------|------|-------------|
| `h264` | H.264 | Hardware-encoded H.264 Baseline/Main |
| `mjpeg` | MJPEG | Motion JPEG |
| `yuy2` | YUY2 | Uncompressed YUYV 4:2:2 |

### 4.3 Extension Unit Controls

Access vendor-specific controls via UVC XU interface:

```python
manager.xu_set(selector=2, value=128)  # Set ISP brightness
value = manager.xu_get(selector=1)     # Get firmware version
```

## 5. REST API

### 5.1 Create Gadget

```
POST /api/uvc-gadget/create
Body: { "gadget_name": "g_uvc", "vendor_id": "0x1d6b", ... }
```

### 5.2 Start Stream

```
POST /api/uvc-gadget/stream/start
Body: { "format": "h264", "width": 1920, "height": 1080, "fps": 30 }
```

### 5.3 Stop Stream

```
POST /api/uvc-gadget/stream/stop
```

### 5.4 Capture Still Image

```
POST /api/uvc-gadget/still/capture
Response: { "path": "/tmp/still_001.jpg", "size": 123456, "resolution": "1920x1080" }
```

### 5.5 Get Status

```
GET /api/uvc-gadget/status
Response: { "state": "streaming", "format": "h264", "resolution": "1920x1080@30fps", ... }
```

## 6. Troubleshooting

| Symptom | Cause | Solution |
|---------|-------|----------|
| Gadget not enumerated | UDC not bound | Check `ls /sys/class/udc/` and bind |
| No /dev/videoN on host | Missing uvcvideo driver | `modprobe uvcvideo` on host |
| Stream freezes | Bandwidth exceeded | Reduce resolution or switch to H.264 |
| XU controls not visible | XU descriptor missing | Verify extension unit in descriptor tree |
| USB-CV fails Chapter 9 | Descriptor error | Re-validate with `validate_descriptors()` |

## 7. USB-CV Compliance Testing

See HIL recipe `hil_usb_cv_compliance` for the full procedure. Summary:

1. Install USB-CV 4.x on Windows host
2. Connect target device
3. Run Chapter 9 + UVC class tests
4. All tests must pass for USB-IF certification

